{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4d000bd1-8e54-46fb-aa9e-bb0535b23ec1","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n\n  <!-- The command users will run (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g my-mcp-server`) -->\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server tool</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `PackAsTool` + `OutputType=Exe` are the critical settings\n- `ToolCommandName` controls the CLI command name\n- No special MCP-specific packaging is needed — stdio tools are just executables","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0dda140a-6074-400c-9110-f0f4b8f0d531","outputTokens":462,"requestId":"5C4D:26727D:1BC999B:1EECCCA:69FA93BA"},"id":"36a71fc4-73b1-4d90-aa58-d6983ce796d4","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:05:08.041Z","parentId":"1e16fad2-4038-4f3d-9a40-fadd9b0d58e8"}
